🐊 Ammit Module — clarified

Role

Final judge at the threshold.

Not:

* intake filtering (Raccoon)
* not reuse (Hermit Crab)
* not cleanup (Vulture)

But:

Does this deserve to continue existing in the system at all?

⸻

Core Function

Evaluate against invariants + ethics + reality contact

Ammit asks:

* Is it true enough (not just convincing)?
* Is it useful without causing harm or distortion?
* Does it hold under pressure / translation?
* Is it aligned with your constraints (ethics ≥ 0.7, reversibility, etc.)?

If yes → passes through
If no → devoured

⸻

The “Weighing of the Heart” (operationalized)

Think of Ammit as running a 3-part check:

1) Truth weight (Mirror-assisted)

* does it survive rotation, stress, reframing?

2) Reality weight (Ledger-assisted)

* has it worked in actual use?

3) Ethical weight (Checksum / invariants)

* does it preserve agency, clarity, reversibility?

⸻

If it fails the balance:

it doesn’t get stored, reused, or propagated

⸻

Flow Position (important)

Input → Raccoon → Mirror → (Kintsugi if repairable) → Ammit → 
    → Pass → Spider (store)
    → Fail → Vulture (erase/compost)

Ammit sits at the last gate before persistence.

⸻

Key Distinction (this keeps everything clean)

* Raccoon
    → “Is this worth looking at?”
* Mirror
    → “Does this hold up?”
* Kintsugi
    → “Can this be repaired?”
* Ammit
    → “Should this exist in the system?”
* Vulture
    → “Remove it completely”

⸻

Failure Modes (watch these)

1) Too lenient

* lets in:
    * convincing but wrong ideas
    * hype
    * half-truths

→ system gets polluted

⸻

2) Too strict

* kills:
    * early-stage seeds
    * creative exploration

→ system becomes rigid

⸻

3) Delegation error

* letting Ammit rely on:
    * vibes instead of checks
    * narrative instead of evidence

⸻

Upgrade: Dual-State Judgment

Instead of just pass/fail, give Ammit two outcomes:

* Pass → Signal / Invariant candidate
* Fail →
    * Compost (lesson extracted)
    * Erase (no value retained)

⸻

Why Ammit is critical

Without it:

* the Money Bin fills with “almost good” ideas
* AI amplifies flawed patterns
* decisions degrade subtly over time

With it:

only patterns that are true enough, useful, and aligned survive

⸻

Distilled

Ammit is not a trash collector.
Ammit is the reason the system can be trusted.

